473","1444–1473":"1444–1473","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1473–1531":"1473–1531","1410–Male":"1410–Overleden","1420–Female":"1420–Overleden","Aft 1473":"na 1473","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1531":"1531","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","Abt 1444":"circa 1444","<1443>":"1443","about 1472":"circa 1472","Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, England","REE, Shrops, Eng.":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1444–Aft 1473":"about 1444–after 1473","1444–1473":"1444–1473","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1473–1531":"1473–1531","1410–Male":"1410–Deceased","1420–Female":"1420–Deceased","Aft 1473":"after 1473","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1531":"1531","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","Abt 1444":"about 1444","<1443>":"1443","about 1472":"about 1472","Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, England","REE, Shrops, Eng.":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ree","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Rea  ; compare   Ray  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of the six farmsteads named <i>Re</i>, the name being derived from an unattested Old Norse word meaning ‘long narrow gravel ridge’.","Korean: variant of   Yi   (compare   Ri   2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rea","meanings":["English: from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter ye</i> ‘at the island’ (Old English <i>ēg</i>, <i>īeg</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on an island or patch of firm ground surrounded by marsh, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rye (Sussex), The Rye in High Wycombe (Buckinghamshire), Rye Hill in Epping Upland (Essex), Rye Mill in Feering (Essex), and Rye House in Stanstead Abbots (Hertfordshire). Alternatively, the name may also arise from a misdivision of the Middle English phrase <i>atter eye</i> ‘at the river’ (Old English <i>ēa</i>) and may also be topographic, for someone who lived near a river or stream, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Rea in Hempsted (Gloucestershire), Ray Lodge in Lingfield (Surrey), and Rye Farm in Cranleigh (Surrey). Due to the similarity of Middle English forms it is now impossible to distinguish between the two explanations. See also   Nye  .","English: post-medieval form of   Wray  .","English: variant of   Ray  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen De Ree was born about 1444, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William de Ree Esq., was 36 and her mother, Elizabeth Rowley, was 26. She married Roger Chetwode about 1472, in Worleston, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1473, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1444–Aft 1473":"umbes 1444–pärast 1473","1444–1473":"1444–1473","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1473–1531":"1473–1531","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","Aft 1473":"pärast 1473","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1531":"1531","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","Abt 1444":"umbes 1444","<1443>":"1443","about 1472":"umbes 1472","Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, England","REE, Shrops, Eng.":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1444–Aft 1473":"noin 1444–1473 jälkeen","1444–1473":"1444–1473","1440–1497":"1440–1497","1473–1531":"1473–1531","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1420–Female":"1420–Kuollut","Aft 1473":"1473 jälkeen","1444":"1444","1410":"1410","1531":"1531","1420":"1420","1497":"1497","1473":"1473","1440":"1440","Abt 1444":"noin 1444","<1443>":"1443","about 1472":"noin 1472","Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, England","REE, Shrops, Eng.":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire